          "population2020": 1984000.0
        }
      ]
    },
    "spatial_features_en": "@Heading The impact of the civil war\nThe 11 years of civil war between 1991 and 2002 and the two wars with neighbouring Liberia (1989-97 and 1999-2003) destabilised the economy, provoked mass population displacement, and resulted in the destruction of several cities and infrastructure in the interior. These crises encouraged concentration in the Freetown metropolitan region and its surroundings, which functioned as a refuge: several interior agglomerations were completely emptied of their populations by the unrest. Despite the Ebola outbreak, which according to the WHO affected 28 000 people and caused 11 000 deaths in 2015-15, small cities and towns have emerged rapidly. However, it will take some time for the destabilised urban system to find a new equilibrium. Some of the destroyed towns are just beginning to re-establish themselves, such as Koindu on the border with Guinea.\n@Image image/countrynote/SLE1EN.png\nOthers have become veritable boomtowns, like Magbema (20 000 inhabitants).\n@Image image/countrynote/SLE2EN.png\n@Heading An urban grid spread over the entire territory\nDespite Freetown's strong growth, the urban structure consists of four medium-sized cities between 100 000 and 200 000 inhabitants spread around the country. These four agglomerations are the political and administrative capitals of the three large provinces: Kenema in the east (200 000 inhabitants), Bo in the south (186 000 inhabitants), Makeni in the north (154 000 inhabitants), to which is also added Koidu, a diamond-mining city (138 000 inhabitants). These were already important centres in the 1970s and have shaped territorial development.",
    "spatial_features_fr": "",
    "urban_forms_en": "",
    "urban_forms_fr": "",
    "territorial_en": "",
    "territorial_fr": ""
